{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605963"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:06:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:06:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15883"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.16,0.2,0.48,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72049"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8574"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57519"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8581"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72049"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring human fertilisation, several critical events must occur in a precise sequence for successful conception.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following events occurs first during fertilisation of a human oocyte?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of the male pronucleus","Cortical reaction and zona hardening","Fusion of sperm and egg membranes","Release of acrosomal enzymes","Formation of the second polar body"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first event in fertilisation is the \u003Cstrong\u003Erelease of acrosomal enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E from the sperm head. These enzymes digest through the zona pellucida, allowing the sperm to reach the egg surface. Subsequently, \u003Cstrong\u003Efusion of sperm and egg membranes\u003C/strong\u003E occurs, triggering the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecortical reaction and zona hardening\u003C/strong\u003E that prevents multiple sperm from entering (polyspermy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter membrane fusion, the egg completes its second meiotic division with \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of the second polar body\u003C/strong\u003E. The sperm nucleus then decondenses to form the \u003Cstrong\u003Emale pronucleus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe precise sequence is essential for successful fertilisation. The acrosome reaction must occur first to allow sperm penetration, followed by membrane fusion which triggers the protective cortical reaction. Nuclear events including polar body formation and pronuclear development occur only after successful sperm entry.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The acrosome reaction releases hydrolytic enzymes that digest through the zona pellucida, enabling sperm penetration of the oocyte.","The cortical reaction prevents polyspermy by hardening the zona pellucida after initial sperm entry.","Sperm-oocyte membrane fusion occurs after penetration of the zona pellucida but before pronuclear formation."],"references":["Reid AT, Redgrove K, Aitken RJ, Nixon B. Cellular mechanisms regulating sperm-zona pellucida interaction. Asian J Androl. 2011 Jan;13(1):88-96. doi: 10.1038/aja.2010.74. Epub 2010 Nov 1. PMID: 21042304; PMCID: PMC3739399","Leung ETY, Lee BKM, Lee CL, Tian X, Lam KKW, Li RHW, Ng EHY, Yeung WSB, Ou JP, Chiu PCN. The role of spermatozoa-zona pellucida interaction in selecting fertilization-competent spermatozoa in humans. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2023 Mar 20;14:1135973. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2023.1135973. PMID: 37020592; PMCID: PMC10067631","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15883"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:44:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:45:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8574"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72049"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descr